üí≥ Credit Card Fraud Detection using Machine Learning

üìå Project Overview
    Credit card fraud is a major challenge for financial institutions due to the highly imbalanced
    nature of transaction data.This project focuses on building an end-to-end machine learning
    pipeline to detect fraudulent credit card transactions using multiple classification
    algorithms and advanced evaluation techniques.

    The project includes:
        1.Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
        2.Data preprocessing and feature scaling
        3.ANOVA-based feature selection
        4.Handling class imbalance using SMOTE
        5.Model training and comparison
        6.Hyperparameter tuning
        7.Model evaluation using fraud-appropriate metrics
        8.Final model selection and deployment readiness using Pickle and Flask

üéØ Objective
    To accurately identify fraudulent transactions while maintaining a balance between:
        1. High Recall (catching frauds)
        2. High Precision (reducing false alarms)

üìÇ Dataset Description
    1.Source: Credit Card Transactions Dataset from kaggle
    2.Target Variable: Class
        0 ‚Üí Non-Fraud
        1 ‚Üí Fraud
    3.Key Characteristics:
        Highly imbalanced dataset
        Numerical features
        Includes Amount and Time attributes

üõ†Ô∏è Technologies & Libraries Used
    1. Programming Language: Python

    2.Libraries:
         pandas, numpy
         matplotlib,seaborn
         scikit-learn
         imbalanced-learn (SMOTE)
         xgboost
         pickle
         Flask (for deployment)

üîÑ Project Workflow
1Ô∏è‚É£ Data Exploration & Analysis
    Checked dataset structure, data types, and missing values
    Analyzed class imbalance
    Visualized:
        Class distribution
        Transaction amount distribution
        Fraud vs non-fraud transactions
        Correlation heatmap
2Ô∏è‚É£ Data Preprocessing
    Removed duplicate records
    Scaled Amount and Time using StandardScaler
    Dropped original unscaled columns
    Split data into training and testing sets using stratified sampling
3Ô∏è‚É£ Feature Selection using ANOVA (f_classif)
    ANOVA evaluates how strongly each feature is related to the target
    Outputs:
    F-score ‚Üí Feature importance
    P-value ‚Üí Statistical significance
    Top features are selected using SelectKBest
4Ô∏è‚É£Handling Class Imbalance
    Applied SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) on training data
    Improved model learning for minority (fraud) class
5Ô∏è‚É£ Model Training
Trained and evaluated the following models:
    Logistic Regression
    Random Forest Classifier
    XGBoost Classifier
    Gradient Boosting classifier
6Ô∏è‚É£ Model Evaluation Metrics
Due to class imbalance, accuracy was avoided.
Instead, the following metrics were used:
    Precision
    Recall
    ROC-AUC
    PR-AUC
    Confusion Matrix
    Precision-Recall Curve
    ROC Curve
7Ô∏è‚É£ Hyperparameter Tuning
    Applied RandomizedSearchCV
    Optimized models using F1-Score
    Tuned parameters for:
        Random Forest
        XGBoost
8Ô∏è‚É£ Final Model Selection
The Tuned Random Forest Classifier was selected as the final model because:
    Higher precision (fewer false positives)
    Strong recall
    Better balance for real-world fraud detection systems

üíæ Model Serialization (Pickle)
To enable deployment:
    The trained model  were serialized using pickle
    Ensures consistent preprocessing and prediction during inference
        model_filename = "credit_card_fraud_random_forest.pkl"
        joblib.dump(best_model, model_filename)
üåê Deployment (Flask)
    A Flask web application loads the pickled model
    Accepts transaction inputs
    Outputs:
        Fraud / Non-Fraud prediction
        Probability score